{
  "doc_id": "20795",
  "text": "• Paresthesia may be caused by selective lacunar infarcts in the diencephalic and mesencephalic regions or in the diaschisis in the parietal cortex. Chang and Huang reported a patient who presented with unilateral paresthesia after acute isolated infarct of the splenium [CITATION_1] . Kim reported that paresthesia or pain occurred between 0 to 24 months after lenticulocapsular hemorrhage, more prominently in the leg than other body parts [CITATION_2] . In another case report, a thalamic lacunar infarct led to sudden isolated left-sided paresthesia involving the face, upper and lower limbs [CITATION_3] . Cheiro-oral syndrome is characterized by paresthesia and sensory impairment confined to the perioral region and ipsilateral fingers or hand, and arises from small stroke-related lesions to various sites between the medulla and cortex [CITATION_4] .",
